The paper deals with the transmission of correlated sources over multiple-user channels, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). The specific channels studied include multiple access relay channels (MARC), interference channels (IC), and interference relay channels (IRC), which are all related to network information theory (cs.NI). The paper also considers the effects of non-ergodic phase shifts on the input signals, which is a topic in signal processing (cs.SI). Additionally, the paper uses source-channel separation and coding techniques, which are relevant to multimedia (cs.MM) and computational complexity (cs.CC).
